00:00:00.070 --> 00:00:02.439
&gt;&gt;Male Commentator:
Thanks everybody for coming to part of the

00:00:02.439 --> 00:00:07.650
series on being fiscally fit. We're deeply
honored and appreciative today to have Dr.

00:00:07.650 --> 00:00:10.169
Burton Malkiel join us from Princeton.

00:00:10.169 --> 00:00:15.269
Dr. Malkiel is a seminal figure in finance
and economics and particularly in personal

00:00:15.269 --> 00:00:16.269
finance.

00:00:16.269 --> 00:00:20.240
Dr. Malkiel not only has a distinguished career
which I'll tell you briefly about, but in

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:25.099
many ways was-was the first person to have
the insight about what is the optimal investment

00:00:25.099 --> 00:00:27.769
strategy, and one that's actually been proven
overtime to-to be effective.

00:00:27.769 --> 00:00:33.682
And while there's a lot of debate about it,
it is one where if you examine the data you'll

00:00:33.682 --> 00:00:38.050
find it actually works over just about any
measurement period, over any economic period

00:00:38.050 --> 00:00:40.690
in the United States, which is a remarkable
achievement.

00:00:40.690 --> 00:00:45.630
He received his Bachelor's Degree and his
MBA from Harvard University and originally

00:00:45.630 --> 00:00:50.309
went into the business world, but always had
an interest in academic economics and eventually

00:00:50.309 --> 00:00:53.090
earned a Doctorate from Princeton University.

00:00:53.090 --> 00:00:57.780
He's the Chemical Bank's Chairman's Professor
of Economics at Princeton and is a two-time

00:00:57.780 --> 00:00:59.739
Chairman of the Economics Department there.

00:00:59.739 --> 00:01:05.770
He served as a member of the Council of Economic
Advisors from 1975 to 1977; President of the

00:01:05.770 --> 00:01:09.500
American Finance Association; and Dean of
the Yale School of Management.

00:01:09.500 --> 00:01:13.920
He also spent 28 years as a Director of the
Vandard-guard Group and is still very actively

00:01:13.920 --> 00:01:18.900
involved in it and a member I believe of the
Board of their international operations.

00:01:18.900 --> 00:01:22.990
One of the things I think you'll learn is
that people vary wildly in their ability to

00:01:22.990 --> 00:01:29.390
assess risk, particularly when it comes to
their personal finances, and Dr. Malkiel will

00:01:29.390 --> 00:01:33.030
give you a tremendous amount of insight into
what works and what doesn't.

00:01:33.030 --> 00:01:36.890
Beyond that the advice I think he'll share
today with you actually has proven to be true,

00:01:36.890 --> 00:01:42.020
it actually works, which is a useful thing
when it comes to advice.

00:01:42.020 --> 00:01:45.020
Many of you had a copy, found a copy of his
Elements of Investing which is his latest

00:01:45.020 --> 00:01:51.210
book; a follow-up to his decades old best-seller
A Random Walk Down Wall Street. I think you'll

00:01:51.210 --> 00:02:01.009
enjoy his talk a great deal and I welcome
Dr. Malkiel to Google.

00:02:01.009 --> 00:02:02.119
[applause]

00:02:02.119 --> 00:02:06.770
&gt;&gt;Dr. Malkiel:
Thanks very much for your kind introduction

00:02:06.770 --> 00:02:10.880
and thank you all for coming. I'm just delighted
to see all of you guys for as-as far as the

00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:13.110
eye can see.

00:02:13.110 --> 00:02:22.350
What I'm gonna do is talk to you today, I-I
call this talk "Timeless Lessons for Investors"

00:02:22.350 --> 00:02:28.990
'cause I wanna talk about what I think are
the timeless lessons and some of them which

00:02:28.990 --> 00:02:32.850
are in fact in question right now.

00:02:32.850 --> 00:02:35.640
[sound of phone ringing in background]

00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:43.500
So let me begin by talking about some things
that people now say we have presumably learned

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:48.000
given the past financial crisis.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:54.451
One of the things that they presumably have
learned is that now you have to time the market.

00:02:54.451 --> 00:03:01.830
After all we realize that we've just been
through a period where the market tanked,

00:03:01.830 --> 00:03:09.520
went down almost 50%, and this shows you that
buy and hold is dead, that that's the wrong

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:11.620
thing to do.

00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:20.720
And basically I don't think that that's correct.
I still believe in buy and hold for the following

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:29.620
reason; obviously if we knew that 2007 was
the top of the market. If we knew that, yes

00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:40.770
we should have sold then and then bought back
in March of, of 2008, 2009 which turned out

00:03:40.770 --> 00:03:44.340
to be the bottom of the market.

00:03:44.340 --> 00:03:50.350
But nobody can do that. You know I've been
in the investment business for a long number

00:03:50.350 --> 00:03:58.410
of years. I have never known anyone who could
consistently time the market, individual or

00:03:58.410 --> 00:04:04.910
professional. And I've never known anyone
who knows anybody who could consistently time

00:04:04.910 --> 00:04:14.170
the market. And the problem is if you try
to do it you are much more likely to be wrong

00:04:14.170 --> 00:04:16.019
than to be right.

00:04:16.019 --> 00:04:24.980
Now, this gives you an example of what people
actually do. And what we've superimposed here

00:04:24.980 --> 00:04:35.680
is the solid line shows you the performance
of the world stock markets and the bar graph

00:04:35.680 --> 00:04:44.190
shows the flow of funds into equity mutual
funds superimposed on how the market is doing.

00:04:44.190 --> 00:04:52.030
And what you notice is that when the market
is high that's when people put their money

00:04:52.030 --> 00:04:59.980
into the market and when the market is low
that's where people take their money out.

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:08.870
More money went into the market during the
Internet boom in late 1999 and early 2000

00:05:08.870 --> 00:05:16.620
than ever before. And then in October of 2002
which was the bottom of the market, more money

00:05:16.620 --> 00:05:26.060
went out than ever before. Similarly in the
late part of the first decade of the 2000's

00:05:26.060 --> 00:05:29.950
when the market was high, the money poured
in.

00:05:29.950 --> 00:05:40.200
And when did the money come out? The money
came out in early, late 2008 and early 2009that

00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:42.870
turned out to be the bottom of the market.

00:05:42.870 --> 00:05:49.020
So, what happens when you try to do that and
you let your emotions tell you? Because after

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:53.760
all what's happening is at the top of the
market all the stories are its optimistic,

00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:58.010
everything's gonna be perfect; at the bottom
of the market the sky is falling, the world's

00:05:58.010 --> 00:06:01.190
gonna end. That's when people take their money
out.

00:06:01.190 --> 00:06:08.560
And so I'd much rather be a buy and hold investor
and just, 'cause I know I can't do it and

00:06:08.560 --> 00:06:10.570
I don't think anybody can do it.

00:06:10.570 --> 00:06:16.560
And the fact is, remember when you try to
time the market you've got to be right now

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:20.900
once but twice. You gotta be right when you
get out; you gotta be right when you get back

00:06:20.900 --> 00:06:22.010
in.

00:06:22.010 --> 00:06:28.900
And because when there are reversals in the
market they happen to quickly, it you take

00:06:28.900 --> 00:06:36.880
a period and this was done from '94 to 2008
where the buy and hold investor had some,

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:42.980
and this was not a great time to be in the
market; it had a 7% return. If you had in

00:06:42.980 --> 00:06:49.690
fact just missed the best 10 days your return
got down to practically nothing. And if you

00:06:49.690 --> 00:06:57.490
had missed the best 30 days and remember those
best days typically were the-the-the leaps

00:06:57.490 --> 00:07:02.240
up right at the bottom of the market when
everyone is pessimistic, you miss those days

00:07:02.240 --> 00:07:08.419
and you actually had a negative return. So,
I say, don't try to time the market. You can't

00:07:08.419 --> 00:07:11.500
do it. It's very dangerous.

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:17.490
Now not only do people make mistakes when
they try to time the market because they get

00:07:17.490 --> 00:07:22.240
in at the top and out at the bottom, but they
buy the wrong kinds of funds.

00:07:22.240 --> 00:07:28.610
Remember I told you more money went into the
stock market in late 1999 and early 2000 than

00:07:28.610 --> 00:07:36.890
ever before? Well what did it go into? It
went into high-tech funds. It didn't go into

00:07:36.890 --> 00:07:43.889
the value funds which were actually very cheap
then, and value stocks actually did well at

00:07:43.889 --> 00:07:51.340
the beginning of the 2000's, but it went into
all of the Internet stocks.

00:07:51.340 --> 00:08:01.560
You know, I remember so vividly as a Director
of the Vanguard Group. Our flagship Vanguard

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:08.550
has generally had a lot of value funds. Our
flagship value funds were losing assets and

00:08:08.550 --> 00:08:17.340
all the assets were being taken out and you
sort of wonder where they were going, because

00:08:17.340 --> 00:08:23.240
when you're in a mutual fund complex and there's
a redemption of a fund it goes into the money

00:08:23.240 --> 00:08:24.240
fund.

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:28.050
So, you have to look at where the checks were
written from the money fund. They were all

00:08:28.050 --> 00:08:33.820
written to this company in Denver called Janus
and they went to something called the Janus

00:08:33.820 --> 00:08:38.480
Twenty Fund which was twenty of their best
stocks, they were all Internet stocks.

00:08:38.480 --> 00:08:47.580
So-so this also this selection penalty that
money went into Internet stocks and out of

00:08:47.580 --> 00:08:53.779
value stocks at the top and again I, without
going through all of the buys and things in

00:08:53.779 --> 00:08:57.050
there, there's also a selection penalty.

00:08:57.050 --> 00:09:04.180
There's a study that was done by a company
called DALBAR. And what it did was it tried

00:09:04.180 --> 00:09:13.490
to compare the returns that are published
by the mutual funds or when you say the stock

00:09:13.490 --> 00:09:22.240
market did a certain rate of return from how
individuals fared. In other words, if let's

00:09:22.240 --> 00:09:29.250
say there's a period and this is a period
from 1988 that this was the DALBAR Study to

00:09:29.250 --> 00:09:35.640
2007. So, it did go to the top of the market.
It's not, this is not indicative of what the

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:39.260
stock market is gonna do in every period.
You had an 11.6% rate of return.

00:09:39.260 --> 00:09:48.870
But if you look at how the average investor
did realizing that the average investor wasn't

00:09:48.870 --> 00:09:54.360
necessarily in the market at the time; that
the average investor didn't buy and hold,

00:09:54.360 --> 00:09:59.100
wasn't buying at the beginning and holding
all the way through, the average investor

00:09:59.100 --> 00:10:00.120
got only 4½%.

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:07.910
And again, that's the danger of trying to
do the timing. You can't do it. It's very

00:10:07.910 --> 00:10:13.790
dangerous. Obviously, with perfect hindsight,
yes you should have timed the market. You

00:10:13.790 --> 00:10:18.410
can't do it. Don't do it. You're more likely
to do it wrong than right.

00:10:18.410 --> 00:10:26.910
And incidentally, this is true not only of
individuals but for institutional investors.

00:10:26.910 --> 00:10:33.240
I have looked at the cash positions of active
managers, whether they're pension funds or

00:10:33.240 --> 00:10:37.270
mutual funds, institutional investors have
more cash at the bottom and the least amount

00:10:37.270 --> 00:10:45.310
of cash at the top. Nobody can do it; neither
amateur nor professional.

00:10:45.310 --> 00:10:56.310
The second timeless lesson is what I will
call the Dollar Cost Averaging lesson.

00:10:56.310 --> 00:11:01.930
Again the argument is, and most of you who
are accumulating, who are saving over time,

00:11:01.930 --> 00:11:10.630
are taking advantage of this. There is an
advantage for putting money into the market

00:11:10.630 --> 00:11:12.500
regularly over time.

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:20.330
So, what this shows you is that even though
the market was rising in what's to the right

00:11:20.330 --> 00:11:30.430
of the screen, you actually made more money
in this volatile flat market than you did

00:11:30.430 --> 00:11:31.430
in the rising market.

00:11:31.430 --> 00:11:37.450
Now, it's not always true. The dollar, obviously
if the market is continuously rising you wanna

00:11:37.450 --> 00:11:39.660
put all your money in at the beginning.

00:11:39.660 --> 00:11:48.550
But if, in fact, we're in a situation of pretty
volatile times, you're more likely to be on

00:11:48.550 --> 00:11:53.940
the left hand side of the screen and at the
very least you're gonna reduce your risk this

00:11:53.940 --> 00:12:01.180
way and the regret that comes if you happen
to put all your money at the, at a market

00:12:01.180 --> 00:12:02.180
top.

00:12:02.180 --> 00:12:08.600
I'm very fond of the advice of Warren Buffett
who likes to give this quiz. So, you plan

00:12:08.600 --> 00:12:13.920
to eat hamburgers all of your life. What would
you prefer? Do want lower prices of hamburgers

00:12:13.920 --> 00:12:19.730
in the future or higher prices? And you know
obviously if you're gonna buy hamburgers you'd

00:12:19.730 --> 00:12:25.450
like lower prices in the future. Or you wanna
buy automobiles throughout your life and you're

00:12:25.450 --> 00:12:32.320
not an automobile manufacturer, you'd prefer
the automobiles to be lower in the future.

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:37.940
And now for the final exam Warren Buffett
says that most people get wrong. So you're

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:44.070
gonna be an-an investor all of your life,
do you want higher prices or lowers prices?

00:12:44.070 --> 00:12:49.709
And the answer is no, you actually would want
lower prices. It's as if you're buying cheaper

00:12:49.709 --> 00:12:53.040
hamburgers or cheaper automobiles.

00:12:53.040 --> 00:12:59.601
It's only when you're close to retirement
that you wanna get into the safer stuff where

00:12:59.601 --> 00:13:05.890
you take things out. And incidentally what
you have actually as part of your options,

00:13:05.890 --> 00:13:10.660
for those of you who are getting closer to
retirement, that's why you have target-maturity

00:13:10.660 --> 00:13:18.860
funds that in fact make sure that you're not
at a time at the end where everything's in

00:13:18.860 --> 00:13:25.870
the stock market when the stock market might
be, might be low and the target funds do exactly

00:13:25.870 --> 00:13:29.330
that for you.

00:13:29.330 --> 00:13:37.090
Now, the other thing that is I think a timeless
lesson is to rebalance, and I say yearly.

00:13:37.090 --> 00:13:47.050
My own work suggests that one oughta rebalance
yearly and this gives you an example from

00:13:47.050 --> 00:14:00.540
January 1996 through December of last year.
That the bottom row says if you were not rebalanced

00:14:00.540 --> 00:14:10.800
you simply start off with a balanced portfolio
of 60% stocks and we'll say you're in an index

00:14:10.800 --> 00:14:18.050
fund what is called generally a total stock
market index fund, which in the Vanguard case

00:14:18.050 --> 00:14:30.630
is with the Russell 3000. and 40% the Broad
Bond Market Index which this says the Lehman,

00:14:30.630 --> 00:14:35.070
unfortunately it's now called the Barclay's
Club of --

00:14:35.070 --> 00:14:36.696
I know something must have happened to Lehman
along the way --

00:14:36.696 --> 00:14:37.696
[laughter]

00:14:37.696 --> 00:14:41.260
I'm not sure what it -- what it was.

00:14:41.260 --> 00:14:47.870
So, if you were not rebalanced you had an
8¾% return.

00:14:47.870 --> 00:14:55.320
And then if you just simply said I wanna be
60/40 and I'm gonna rebalance every year,

00:14:55.320 --> 00:15:01.519
that's what the top row suggests. So, every
year you look at the portfolio if you're away

00:15:01.519 --> 00:15:10.700
from 60/40 you go back to 60/40. And you have
a rate of return that's well over 1% point

00:15:10.700 --> 00:15:11.700
higher.

00:15:11.700 --> 00:15:15.860
So, why does it work? Well, it works for the
following reason. Just think. You can't time

00:15:15.860 --> 00:15:22.180
the market but let's say we're gonna rebalance
in January of every year.

00:15:22.180 --> 00:15:31.920
So, you started off 60/40, we're now in, say,
January of 2000. You don't know it's the top

00:15:31.920 --> 00:15:37.840
of the market. Nobody knows it's the top of
the market. But what you do know is that your

00:15:37.840 --> 00:15:43.810
stocks are sky high and the Federal Reserve
was increasing interest rates which means

00:15:43.810 --> 00:15:50.459
bond prices fell and your bonds were low.
So, you might have had 75%t in stocks and

00:15:50.459 --> 00:15:55.709
25% in bonds, and so you say you take some
money off the table, you take it from the

00:15:55.709 --> 00:15:58.610
stocks and put it into the bonds.

00:15:58.610 --> 00:16:04.480
You're then January of 2003. You don't know
you're just after the lull of the market,

00:16:04.480 --> 00:16:09.130
but what you found was the Federal Reserve
had lowered interest rates so bond prices

00:16:09.130 --> 00:16:16.150
were up. So, your bonds might have been 50,
55%; stocks were in the tank. So, stocks were

00:16:16.150 --> 00:16:21.950
well below your target and so you then sold
some bonds and bought some stocks.

00:16:21.950 --> 00:16:30.320
That's why this works and rebalancing, again
if the stock market does nothing but go up,

00:16:30.320 --> 00:16:38.360
go straight up even then what it-it'll work
in that it gives you much less volatility,

00:16:38.360 --> 00:16:43.410
but you won't quite get the extra return.
But again, if we're gonna be in volatile markets,

00:16:43.410 --> 00:16:50.140
rebalancing is-is gonna not only reduce your
volatility but it's going to increase your

00:16:50.140 --> 00:16:52.149
rate of return.

00:16:52.149 --> 00:16:58.570
Now, the other timeless lesson that I hear
all the time saying, "Boy diversification

00:16:58.570 --> 00:17:09.750
doesn't work anymore." We learned that in
2008 and early 2009 there were few places

00:17:09.750 --> 00:17:17.889
to hide: everything went down together; emerging
markets went down; the U.S. market went down.

00:17:17.889 --> 00:17:24.059
Diversification doesn't work anymore. That's
I-I can't tell ya how often I read that.

00:17:24.059 --> 00:17:32.999
Well, first of all if you were in bonds, if
you had some bonds in your portfolio, diversification

00:17:32.999 --> 00:17:33.999
did work.

00:17:33.999 --> 00:17:40.799
What we know about diversification, you get
the most benefit when you buy an asset class

00:17:40.799 --> 00:17:50.510
that tends to be uncorrelated or very lowly
correlated with, say your main asset is U.S.

00:17:50.510 --> 00:17:57.340
Stocks. Bonds actually have become a better
diversifier over time in that the correlations

00:17:57.340 --> 00:18:01.980
have actually fallen. So, there were places
to hide.

00:18:01.980 --> 00:18:08.090
In fact, in fact what happened with bonds
was the Federal Reserve was reducing interest

00:18:08.090 --> 00:18:16.669
rates to essentially zero and bond prices
were going up. So, bonds were a place to hide.

00:18:16.669 --> 00:18:24.409
Now. it's true that all world stock markets
became very highly correlated, and globalization

00:18:24.409 --> 00:18:32.600
has tended to increase the correlations among
markets. But even though the correlations

00:18:32.600 --> 00:18:42.019
have gone up, it still paid to be diversified
internationally because here you have a graph

00:18:42.019 --> 00:18:51.230
of the emerging markets in the decade from
2000 to 2010.

00:18:51.230 --> 00:18:56.389
And it's something that people often call
the lost decade because it was not a good

00:18:56.389 --> 00:19:04.159
time. These are worldwide stocks. It was not
a good time to be in the stock market. You

00:19:04.159 --> 00:19:10.879
ended up about the same place that you began,
but emerging markets gave you a 10% annual

00:19:10.879 --> 00:19:12.109
rate of return.

00:19:12.109 --> 00:19:19.070
So, even though the ups and downs are the
same, it-it's the fact that they look like

00:19:19.070 --> 00:19:23.649
they're very highly correlated and they are
highly correlated, that still didn't mean

00:19:23.649 --> 00:19:29.419
that you didn't wanna be diversified because
you did much better if you were diversified

00:19:29.419 --> 00:19:33.129
and had some of the emerging markets.

00:19:33.129 --> 00:19:39.690
And again, let's sort of put these things
together, the advantages of diversification,

00:19:39.690 --> 00:19:43.609
rebalancing, and Dollar Cost Averaging.

00:19:43.609 --> 00:19:49.620
You have at the bottom of the slide the lost
decade, you were in the S&amp;P 500, you didn't

00:19:49.620 --> 00:19:55.749
make a penny, you in fact lost some money.
And in the tops part of the graph it says

00:19:55.749 --> 00:20:01.889
you're diversified, you have bonds, you have
some international stocks including emerging

00:20:01.889 --> 00:20:08.360
market stocks, and you do a little bit of
Dollar Cost Averaging. And in the first case

00:20:08.360 --> 00:20:14.759
your hundred thousand dollars declines to
eighty thousand dollars and in the second

00:20:14.759 --> 00:20:19.690
case your hundred thousand dollars goes up
to two hundred and fifty thousand dollars.

00:20:19.690 --> 00:20:28.559
So, it basically just gives you some numbers
to go away with what I've called the timeless

00:20:28.559 --> 00:20:35.389
lessons, that by diversifying, Dollar Cost
Averaging, and rebalancing you get a much

00:20:35.389 --> 00:20:36.820
better investment performance.

