absolutely the case. As the founder of the

00:21:33.850 --> 00:21:41.830
Vanguard Group, Jack Bogle, likes to say,
"In the investment business, you get what

00:21:41.830 --> 00:21:43.979
you don't pay for."

00:21:43.979 --> 00:21:44.979
[laughter]

00:21:44.979 --> 00:21:51.730
And what this does is it breaks down all mutual
funds and these are not just, these are actively

00:21:51.730 --> 00:21:57.799
managed funds, this is every mutual fund there
is in the United States, and it divides them

00:21:57.799 --> 00:22:07.039
into quartiles. The low-cost quartile has
lowest turnover and the lowest explicit expense

00:22:07.039 --> 00:22:17.049
ratio. The high-cost quartile has the highest
costs and the highest portfolio turnover.

00:22:17.049 --> 00:22:26.869
And the low-cost quartile gives you an 8.66%rate
of return. The high co-cost quartile gave

00:22:26.869 --> 00:22:36.629
you a 6.66 and this is the period 1994 through
the end of last year - the end of '09. So

00:22:36.629 --> 00:22:40.119
you've got two percentage points more a year.

00:22:40.119 --> 00:22:46.929
And I've done all kinds of studies for how
do ya pick the mutual funds that do best.

00:22:46.929 --> 00:22:55.720
The only thing that is reliably related to
how mutual funds do is the costs they charge.

00:22:55.720 --> 00:23:03.299
And so, the one thing you can control of the
costs you pay, you want to have funds that

00:23:03.299 --> 00:23:08.600
charge the lowest in expenses.

00:23:08.600 --> 00:23:14.919
And that brings me to one of my favorite subjects
is that you ought to also use, at least to

00:23:14.919 --> 00:23:24.379
some extent, index funds because the quintessential
lo- cost funds are index funds that simply

00:23:24.379 --> 00:23:33.620
buy and hold a broad portfolio and charge
minimal, I mean it, they're very close to

00:23:33.620 --> 00:23:35.260
zero expense ratios.

00:23:35.260 --> 00:23:42.360
Now, I've always argued that index funds make
sense first of all because markets are reasonably

00:23:42.360 --> 00:23:49.419
efficient. You know, there are a lot of very
smart people out there looking for every opportunity

00:23:49.419 --> 00:23:57.919
to buy cheap stocks and they therefore give
you a tableau of market prices that makes

00:23:57.919 --> 00:24:01.919
it very difficult to find really cheap stuff.

00:24:01.919 --> 00:24:07.149
You know, the way we academics like to tell
this is the sort of story about the efficient

00:24:07.149 --> 00:24:12.340
market professor who is walking along with
a couple of graduate students and the graduate

00:24:12.340 --> 00:24:16.419
students see a hundred dollar bill on the
ground and one of the graduate students stoops

00:24:16.419 --> 00:24:22.559
to pick it up and the professors says, "Don't
bother to pick it up. If it were really a

00:24:22.559 --> 00:24:24.309
hundred dollar bill it wouldn't be there."

00:24:24.309 --> 00:24:25.309
[laughter]

00:24:25.309 --> 00:24:31.139
You know I'm not quite that extreme. I tell,
I tell the graduate student, "Pick it up right

00:24:31.139 --> 00:24:33.039
away because it isn't gonna be there for long."

00:24:33.039 --> 00:24:34.039
[laughter]

00:24:34.039 --> 00:24:40.330
I mean we-we just don't leave hundred dollar
bills on the ground very long.

00:24:40.330 --> 00:24:45.119
So, that's one reason why you oughta be in
index funds, but even if you don't agree with

00:24:45.119 --> 00:24:51.330
me that markets are pretty efficient, indexing
still have to be an optimal strategy because

00:24:51.330 --> 00:24:58.769
when you think about it investing has to be
a zero-sum game.

00:24:58.769 --> 00:25:07.919
That is to say we're all different investors,
we buy different stocks, it's since all the

00:25:07.919 --> 00:25:16.409
stocks have to be held by somebody, it must
be that if I just buy the stocks that go up

00:25:16.409 --> 00:25:26.139
the most, somebody else has had to have the
stocks that didn't go up. Th-this is just

00:25:26.139 --> 00:25:34.820
we-we don't live in Lake Wobegon. We cannot
all be above; we can't all be above average.

00:25:34.820 --> 00:25:41.049
So, if you think of it then, that if half
the people are better than the market, half

00:25:41.049 --> 00:25:46.960
of them have to be below the market, you realize
it's a zero-sum game. But in the presence

00:25:46.960 --> 00:25:56.249
of costs, if you now say that on average,
and this is the, this is true, that on average

00:25:56.249 --> 00:26:03.970
purveyors of investment products charge one
percentage point in costs, that means that

00:26:03.970 --> 00:26:13.229
if the market does 8% you've shifted the whole
distribution over in that everybody's gonna

00:26:13.229 --> 00:26:20.879
get whatever they got from their portfolio
minus the 1% of cost. It then must be that

00:26:20.879 --> 00:26:23.080
most people will underperform the market.

00:26:23.080 --> 00:26:31.279
If you could buy an index fund that has the
whole market at essentially zero cost and

00:26:31.279 --> 00:26:38.009
that's really the, you know, it's a matter
of arithmetic that since index funds are available

00:26:38.009 --> 00:26:46.009
at, you know, something like a ri-right around
a tenth of 1%, essentially zero cost, it has

00:26:46.009 --> 00:26:52.019
to be that as a matter of logic they're going
to outperform most other managers.

00:26:52.019 --> 00:26:59.799
And I look at this stuff I-I said you oughta
be in index funds before index funds even

00:26:59.799 --> 00:27:00.799
existed.

00:27:00.799 --> 00:27:06.049
I'm actually working on the tenth edition
of my book, A Random Walk Down Wall Street.

00:27:06.049 --> 00:27:11.720
And every time I do it and these are data
that I'll put in the new edition, every time

00:27:11.720 --> 00:27:19.529
I look at it, look at the last year, look
at the last 20 years, you see generally ? of

00:27:19.529 --> 00:27:25.549
investors of funds are beaten by an index
fund.

00:27:25.549 --> 00:27:34.250
And it doesn't matter whether it's a-all funds,
all large cap funds, all mid cap funds, all

00:27:34.250 --> 00:27:38.659
small cap funds, multi-cap funds, global,
international.

00:27:38.659 --> 00:27:47.789
Even in emerging markets, 90% of active managers
are beaten. And the reason that more are beaten

00:27:47.789 --> 00:27:54.759
in emerging markets which are probably less
efficient is that they, the expenses of dealing

00:27:54.759 --> 00:28:00.190
with emerging markets and the problems of
tryin' to do a lot of turnover in trading

00:28:00.190 --> 00:28:06.659
because there are stamp taxes, they're a lot
of taxes in emerging markets, even there indexing

00:28:06.659 --> 00:28:09.269
works even better.

00:28:09.269 --> 00:28:17.600
When you look at a-a very long period and
I will just tell the people who can't see

00:28:17.600 --> 00:28:27.320
the charts, what I've done here is taken a
look at every mutual fund that existed in

00:28:27.320 --> 00:28:37.090
1970. And in 1970, there were 358 mutual funds.
There's so every mutual fund that existed.

00:28:37.090 --> 00:28:45.519
And then I look at how they did up through
2009. And the first thing that you, people

00:28:45.519 --> 00:28:57.739
will notice who can see the chart is there
were only 119 that are still around, from

00:28:57.739 --> 00:28:59.480
the 358 that started.

00:28:59.480 --> 00:29:03.820
And all I can do is plot how the 119 did.
So, these data have what we call survivorship

00:29:03.820 --> 00:29:12.499
bias in them, because the 239 that didn't
survive I can assure you had much worse records.

00:29:12.499 --> 00:29:19.779
Because there's kind of a, a nasty young,
a nasty secret in the mutual fund business

00:29:19.779 --> 00:29:25.849
and that is mutual funds are normally in big
complexes. You know the Fidelity Group, the

00:29:25.849 --> 00:29:28.009
American Funds Group.

00:29:28.009 --> 00:29:34.129
If you have in your complex a fund that hasn't
done well, you normally kill the fund by merging

00:29:34.129 --> 00:29:39.289
it into a fund that had a better record. So,
that's why there's a lot of survivorship bias

00:29:39.289 --> 00:29:46.830
in this, but even with the survivorship what
it shows you is the distribution looks like

00:29:46.830 --> 00:29:52.909
the theoretical distribution that most of
its on the negative side. And in fact, you

00:29:52.909 --> 00:30:00.519
can count on the fingers of one hand, the
number of funds that started in 1970 that

00:30:00.519 --> 00:30:02.639
had beaten the market by two percentage points
or more.

00:30:02.639 --> 00:30:10.779
It's not that you can't, it's not that there
are no examples. I sometimes say, "You know

00:30:10.779 --> 00:30:14.179
if I'd know Warren Buffett would have been
Warren Buffett, I might have said in my books

00:30:14.179 --> 00:30:20.460
that was first published in 1973 by Berkshire
Hathaway, "forget about index funds."

00:30:20.460 --> 00:30:25.049
And you know what? There will be some Warren
Buffetts in the future. There may be several

00:30:25.049 --> 00:30:29.730
of them. But the problem is I don't know who
they are and I'll bet you don't know who they

00:30:29.730 --> 00:30:35.019
are and when you try to find, them you're
much more likely to be on the negative side

00:30:35.019 --> 00:30:41.179
of the distribution. It's like looking for
a needle in the haystack and I guess what

00:30:41.179 --> 00:30:45.250
I'm saying is buy the low cost haystack instead.

00:30:45.250 --> 00:30:46.250
[laughter]

00:30:46.250 --> 00:30:54.809
Now, you always will see examples of and-and-and
the financial press loves to do that. These

00:30:54.809 --> 00:30:59.450
funds beat the index ten times in a row. You
see this all the time.

00:30:59.450 --> 00:31:03.590
So this, I didn't even do this chart, I picked
it up from the Wall Street Journal a year

00:31:03.590 --> 00:31:11.919
ago. And it said there were 14 funds that
had beaten the index for 9 consecutive years

00:31:11.919 --> 00:31:20.159
and then how many actually beat the index
the next year. And out of the 14 there was

00:31:20.159 --> 00:31:25.240
only 1 that beat the index; 13 of the 14 did
worse than the index.

00:31:25.240 --> 00:31:31.960
What it shows you is you can't pick a fund
by simply saying, "This manager beat the index

00:31:31.960 --> 00:31:38.289
for a certain number of years." It doesn't
work that way. The only thing, and I've done

00:31:38.289 --> 00:31:45.539
statistical work on this for years, the only
thing that's reliably related to fund returns

00:31:45.539 --> 00:31:48.029
is the costs that they charge.

00:31:48.029 --> 00:31:56.499
In the bond market area, it's exactly the
same thing. Bonds are very close to commodity

00:31:56.499 --> 00:32:07.019
products and again ? or more of bond managers
are beaten by a bond index funds.

00:32:07.019 --> 00:32:14.849
Now, I don't say and I don't even myself simply
have every bit of my money in index funds.

00:32:14.849 --> 00:32:23.339
But what I do suggest one does is what professional
investors do more and more and that is at

00:32:23.339 --> 00:32:29.600
least the core of one's portfolio, there's
enough evidence that indexing works, that

00:32:29.600 --> 00:32:38.369
at least the core of your portfolio oughta
be in low cost index funds. And then if you

00:32:38.369 --> 00:32:52.549
wanna buy an individual stock or take a-a-a
flyer on buying Cambodian stock, fine you

00:32:52.549 --> 00:32:58.529
can do it with much less risk if the core
of your portfolio is indexed.

00:32:58.529 --> 00:33:06.900
And this is what professional investors increasingly
do. Pension funds and even universities that

00:33:06.900 --> 00:33:12.580
do a lot of private investing, to the extent
that they hold public stock they will index

00:33:12.580 --> 00:33:19.460
the public part of it and then do the private
stuff, stuff as active.

00:33:19.460 --> 00:33:25.599
So, let me go back to diversification again
and this'll be the last point that I will

00:33:25.599 --> 00:33:29.539
make 'cause I do wanna leave some time for
questions.

00:33:29.539 --> 00:33:44.779
I have suggested to you that what you want
to do is to be broadly indexed. You don't

00:33:44.779 --> 00:33:55.159
want just one stock. And incidentally even
though you guys will all have positions in

00:33:55.159 --> 00:34:02.440
a great stock, Google, you don't want all
of your money in Google because ev, bad things

00:34:02.440 --> 00:34:09.210
sometimes even happen to good companies. It's
