informal advisor to a-a number of the widow's
of faculty members at Princeton. And I really

01:06:12.980 --> 01:06:24.490
do understand how emotions and one's capacity
to take risk is important.

01:06:24.490 --> 01:06:31.020
There was one widow, she was only fifty years
old, her husband died very young, and she

01:06:31.020 --> 01:06:37.480
was just so nervous and we were trying to
think of what's an optimal mix of stocks and

01:06:37.480 --> 01:06:44.670
bonds. And normally for someone who is fifty
you'd think that at least half in stocks,

01:06:44.670 --> 01:06:47.780
maybe more would be appropriate.

01:06:47.780 --> 01:06:59.440
But she was just so terribly nervous we agreed
on, we agreed on one-third stocks and two-thirds

01:06:59.440 --> 01:07:11.010
bonds. And it's now the beginning of last
year, all hell is breaking loose, and she

01:07:11.010 --> 01:07:16.790
comes into my office in absolute tears, "I
can't take it anymore. I have to sell all

01:07:16.790 --> 01:07:17.970
my stocks."

01:07:17.970 --> 01:07:25.570
Now, if I were just coldly thinking of the
right thing to do I'd say, "Hey, this is the

01:07:25.570 --> 01:07:29.160
time to rebalance; put more into the stock
[chuckles] market."

01:07:29.160 --> 01:07:30.160
[laughter]

01:07:30.160 --> 01:07:32.800
All I could do is keep her from selling her
stocks –

01:07:32.800 --> 01:07:33.800
[laughter]

01:07:33.800 --> 01:07:39.720
and-and so that's a factor as well. Some,
one's temperament is certainly a factor. The-the

01:07:39.720 --> 01:07:48.241
old line was the, J.P. Morgan was asked by
a friend, the friend said, "Hey, look what

01:07:48.241 --> 01:07:54.830
should I do? The stock market's going up and
down; I can't take it anymore. I can't sleep

01:07:54.830 --> 01:07:59.790
at night. What should I do?" And J.P. Morgan
said, "Well, sell down to the sleeping point."

01:07:59.790 --> 01:08:00.790
[laughter]

01:08:00.790 --> 01:08:06.930
So it really is partly and-and this is partly
an emotional thing, so I think all of those

01:08:06.930 --> 01:08:13.330
are factors. And I can't just give you one,
one answer, but I think given you some idea

01:08:13.330 --> 01:08:16.150
of the direction in which I would put things.

01:08:16.150 --> 01:08:18.779
[pause]

01:08:18.779 --> 01:08:21.250
One more question, th-the hook is coming.

01:08:21.250 --> 01:08:22.250
[laughter]

01:08:22.250 --> 01:08:25.170
&gt;&gt;male in audience #6:
Thank you. In your book you talk a lot about

01:08:25.170 --> 01:08:30.249
saving as well as an in-investing and I'm
wondering if you could give some guidance

01:08:30.249 --> 01:08:35.630
a-as to what would be a good targets to save
maybe at different ages and percentages.

01:08:35.630 --> 01:08:42.759
&gt;&gt;Professor Malkiel:
Yeah, I think for most people I would just

01:08:42.759 --> 01:08:45.089
say more. I mean it's --

01:08:45.089 --> 01:08:46.089
[laughter]

01:08:46.089 --> 01:08:55.239
it-it's, I don't think preaching to you guys
I have to do because I have learned at lunch

01:08:55.239 --> 01:09:00.909
that you now have a 401k where 99% of the
people are in.

01:09:00.909 --> 01:09:08.889
Where I really have to do the-the-the saving
pre-preaching is so many people in so many

01:09:08.889 --> 01:09:20.929
companies are not part of their 401k and they
save absolutely, they save absolutely nothing.

01:09:20.929 --> 01:09:28.549
And some people don't even join the company
401k when up to the match of the company.

01:09:28.549 --> 01:09:38.579
So I-I'm not sure that with your 401k that
you have here that this is something where

01:09:38.579 --> 01:09:45.080
you all are doing something that's, that's
wrong.

01:09:45.080 --> 01:09:54.279
But I think in general I would say, I would
say this: I don't think you have to save quite

01:09:54.279 --> 01:10:00.179
as much if you start early because you've
got that compounding affect.

01:10:00.179 --> 01:10:09.080
And where I think you really need to save
which could be 15 or 20% or even more of your

01:10:09.080 --> 01:10:15.889
income are those people who did no saving
at all when they were young and they're now

01:10:15.889 --> 01:10:24.219
looking at retiring in 15 years and those
folks have to save a very high percentage.

01:10:24.219 --> 01:10:32.479
So I'd say again, I don't wanna give a particular
number, but less if you're young, more if

01:10:32.479 --> 01:10:38.219
you're older.
And also to think and people I think don't

01:10:38.219 --> 01:10:44.120
do this, but maybe every once in a while,
even if you don't keep a budget, to look at,

01:10:44.120 --> 01:10:50.210
"What did I spend money on last month." And
ask yourself, "Do I really have a lot of stuff

01:10:50.210 --> 01:10:59.329
that really didn't give me much satisfaction?
Did I need all of that stuff?"

01:10:59.329 --> 01:11:06.940
Remembering that the opportunity cost of not
saving when you're in your 20's the opportunity

01:11:06.940 --> 01:11:17.789
cost of not saving a dollar might be 10, 15,
20 dollars in your 50's and 60's. So, the

01:11:17.789 --> 01:11:30.239
opportunity cost is higher when you're younger.
And you ought to at least think of those,

01:11:30.239 --> 01:11:34.489
think of those kinds of things, but I think
you guys are --

01:11:34.489 --> 01:11:35.489
